                            <comment id="16559554" author="sebb@apache.org" created="Fri, 27 Jul 2018 10:40:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No need; you can extend Observer with your own class and pass that to ObservableInputStream#add(Observer)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See for example MessageDigestCalculatingInputStream.MessageDigestMaintainingObserver&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16559710" author="jochen@apache.org" created="Fri, 27 Jul 2018 12:56:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I disagree, sebb, because the MessageCalculatingInputStream is in the same package, thus can easily use package-private methods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16559711" author="jochen@apache.org" created="Fri, 27 Jul 2018 12:56:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed, will be in 2.7, whenever that comes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16559794" author="bpalos" created="Fri, 27 Jul 2018 13:55:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thank you!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16560324" author="sebb@apache.org" created="Fri, 27 Jul 2018 21:02:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Oops, my bad, overlooked that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, I wonder whether it makes sense to have to override the nested Observer class in order to use the ObservableInputStream.&lt;br/&gt;
Seems a bit messy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Would it not be better to use an interface instead? &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That aspect of the design can be changed now without breaking compatibility.&lt;br/&gt;
Once the methods are made protected they become part of the API.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
